World football has experienced something of a transformation over the past 15 years, an increase in investment, increased attendance, increased revenue from a variety of different sources and there are encouraging evidence that each them are adopting different methods to remain competitive. It is well known that some teams need a certain degree of competitive balance in order to survive and flourish. Player profitability is a great way to not only remain competitive but it is also a good way for a low-ranking team to achieve rapid success. When we consider player profitability, what does that actually represent? Player profitability would be a method of determining the success or Potential of a certain player based on a set of predetermined characteristics. With so much at stake and the transfer fees for players constantly increasing, the search for talent has become more desperate with football teams fighting to achieve the best talent.

Effective sports analytics has greatly helped in baseball and basketball in determining the competitive characteristics using statistics. On the other hand, analytics for world football is fairly limited; it will be beneficial to establish a few analytics methods that may help better provide insightful results. The purpose of our analysis is to predict the potential of a player surrounding certain characteristics that are highlighted for currently successful players in those positions.

Dataset

The data was taken from the FIFA 19 complete player data. It consist of 18207 attributes and 89 variables like Age, Nationality, Overall, Potential, Club, Value, Wage, Preferred Foot, International Reputation, Weak Foot, Skill Moves, Work Rate, Position, Jersey Number, Joined, Loaned From, Contract Valid Until, Height, Weight, LS, ST, RS, LW, LF, CF, RF, RW, LAM, CAM, RAM, LM, LCM, CM, RCM, RM, LWB, LDM, CDM, RDM, RWB, LB, LCB, CB, RCB, RB, Crossing, Finishing, Heading, Accuracy, Short-Passing, Volleys, Dribbling, Curve, FK-Accuracy, Long-Passing, Ball-Control, Acceleration, Sprint-Speed, Agility, Reactions, Balance, Shot-Power, Jumping, Stamina, Strength, Long-Shots, Aggression, Interceptions, Positioning, Vision, Penalties, Composure, Marking, Standing-Tackle, Sliding-Tackle, GK-Diving, GK-Handling, GK-Kicking, GK-Positioning, GK-Reflexes, and Release Clause.

Analysis

Q: What is the distribution of the age of the players? How is it related to the average rating?

#Age Density of FIFA Players

fifa2019_unique <- 
  fifa2019 %>% 
  group_by(Name) %>% 
  top_n(n = 1, wt = ID) %>%
  as.data.frame()

age_rating <- fifa2019_unique %>% 
              group_by(Age) %>% 
              summarise(Age_Count = n(),Average_Rating = mean(Overall))

obj1 <- xyplot(Age_Count ~ Age, age_rating, type = "h", lwd = 15)
obj2 <- xyplot(Average_Rating ~ Age, age_rating, type = "l", lwd = 3)


doubleYScale(obj1, obj2,add.ylab2 = TRUE)

As we can see in the plot above, the age of maximum number of the players is between 20 and 26 years.There is decrease in the number of players after age of 27 and the number falls rapidly after age of 30. The reason could that many young players give up their dream if they do not succeed in sports career. As the players gain experience with age, their rating increases and their peak ratings are in the age range of 30-34. Then, after 35, the physical fitness starts decreasing so it impact their rating. Most of them take retirement from football. Surprisingly, there are players 22 players in the age range of 40-45 who maintain an excellent rating and possibly because they are able keep themselves fit and active.

fifa2019_unique$Position <- gsub("/*.^", "", fifa2019_unique$Position )

Q: How is a player’s skill set influence his potential? Can we predict a player’s potential based on his skills’ set?

Conclusion and insights

We ran a few regression models but settled on fifalm model. We found that Penalties, sliding tackles, Goal Keeper kicking and Goal Keeper positioning were statistically insignificant in predicting the potential of a player. We tested the model on fifa_test and calculated an RMSE of 4.65. This model has R-squared value 0.41 which means that 41% of the variation of y has been explained by the independent variable. We tried to identify the most important attributes relating to player performance that contributes to a player’s potential. The attributes are crossing, finishing, heading accuracy, short passing, volleys, dribbling, curve, free kick accuracy, long passing, ball control, acceleration, sprint speed, agility, reactions, balance, shot power, jumping, stamina, strength, long shot, aggression, interception, positioning, vision, composure, marking, standing tackle, goal keeper diving, goal keeper handling, goal keeper reflexes.

Earlier we stated the competitive steps teams are undertaking to either remain at the top of their leagues or reduce the gap between the top of the league and the bottom from a financial prospective. The ability to predict the potential of a player given their attributes will prove insightful in two significant ways,

  1. Development opportunities and
  2. Player’s worth

And this is possible with enough historical data on what attributes that contribute to the success of players in various leagues. Teams can easily determine what attributes to develop based on player position on the field.
